flowRoot.flowPara: Lead designer and team manager of the design and user experience team.
Client interaction: project initiation, requirement gathering, competitive analysis, presentation
Interaction and visual design with high fidelity HTML mockups as deliverables
Uniquely positioned to meet developers needs with a background in coding
Firm-wide HTML5, CSS3, and JS consultant
Designed multiple products end-to-end:
Employee performance appraisal system
Recruitment and employee referral portal
Immigration and travel tracker
Roadmap tracker (with complete UI dev)
Trend analysis tool
Post trade workflow dashboard
Retail investment app (with complete UI dev)
Designed new features and performed heuristic evaluation of existing products
Maintained the firm's corporate websites
Resource allocation, expectation management, project planning, status reporting, and performance appraisals

Ported features from v1.0 to v2.0 of Microsoft Mobile Communicator, a WinCE 5.0 IM/VOIP client running in tandem with Microsoft Office technologies, required by changes in the underlying IM/VOIP framework. It was a short stint because of lack of UI work.

Full product suite i18n from scratch, including the ability to manage web-services with end-points, APIs, and parameters with multibyte character names. Also responsible for a product called the Environment Monitor, which was AmberPoints JFC/Swing UI.

I was a campus hire for Veritas. I worked on a UI integration platform in JFC/Swing called the Veritas Enterprise Administrator, the front end for an object bus used to remotely manage storage solutions:
Design and development of the framework, product features, and components
Profiling and performance testing; optimization
Finding and fixing memory leaks, writing new client-server event mechanisms, implementing a single sign-on UI

I am an avid runner, marathoner, and cyclist. I also read SF and fantasy and enjoy the occasional first-person shooter. An unabashed geek, I follow the latest science news and tech blogs. My latest form of nerdy entertain-ment is tinkering with my Raspberry Pi.
